text.tspan: smrt: A Three-dimensional
Media Center User Interface
The Ring Menu
The ring menu distributes its items laid out in a circle,
viewed from above. When navigating between items, the
circle spins. The result of this layout is that the "selected"
item is naturally in the center and largest on the screen.
In addition, the ring menu reduces the amount of
interaction a user has to perform in order to navigate to
any particular item. With a regular list, getting to the
bottom icon would require n button presses (where n is the
number of items. Because the ring menu can spin in either
direction, at most only n/2 button presses are required.

flowRoot.flowPara: The arc menu places menu items in an arc at the right of the screen. The items move up and down as the user navigates the menu. Like the ring menu, the central item - the largest one - is the currently selected item.

The layout of the arc menu makes it specially suited for displaying additional information alongside the menu. It's purpose in smrt's default configuration is as a television program guide. Each menu item represents a channel; beside the menu is a display showing the current program on the channel and a schedule for the channel.

text.tspan: The Challenges of the Living Room
Display Resolution
A modern computer screen is a very high resolution output
device with a fast refresh rate. In contrast, a standard
NTSC television displays a very low quality picture. This
limits the amount of information that can be shown, and
makes the display of text a challenge.

Input Devices
Within the living room, there is no keyboard or mouse, not
to mention the advanced 3-D input devices traditionally
used for 3D user interfaces. Even within the scope of
remote controls, there are very complex and very simple
examples. Apple Inc.'s "Front Row" remote control has
only 6 buttons.
Due to the wide variety in remote
control features, the smrt
interface is designed to work with
only a small number of buttons.
The four directional buttons, an
"enter" button and an "escape"
button are the only ones required
to navigate through the menus.

text.tspan: TM
The Cityscape Menu

flowRoot.flowPara: The cityscape menu represents menu items as buildings; buildings are arranged in a grid, creating a city. Buildings are allowed to contain other buildings. These sub-buildings are displayed atop the building containing them. If a building containing sub-buildings is activated, the camera zooms in to the roof of that building and displays the sub-buildings in another cityscape menu.

The grid arrangement of buildings provides non-linear access to the items in the menu,making the cityscape ideal for browsing large media collections. Additionally, the sub-building concept is very useful for identifying directories and files when using the cityscape menu as a file browser.
